I am going to split.

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:24.730
- Okay.

00:48:24.730 --> 00:48:26.520
This is serious money.

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:27.650
- Okay.

00:48:27.650 --> 00:48:32.650
Now, we're gonna take a vote
on what you think happens.

00:48:32.909 --> 00:48:35.159
(laughing)

00:48:37.679 --> 00:48:40.874
All right, there's two
decisions, split or to steal.

00:48:40.874 --> 00:48:43.670
You couldn't see the faces, but probably

00:48:43.670 --> 00:48:45.260
doesn't matter that much.

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:50.260
How many of you think
that the guy will split?

00:48:55.431 --> 00:48:56.560
Okay.

00:48:56.560 --> 00:48:59.693
How many think the gal will split?

00:49:02.072 --> 00:49:05.830
Slightly more, but about 50/50.

00:49:07.067 --> 00:49:09.473
Okay, here's what happens.

00:49:10.586 --> 00:49:12.220
- Here it is.

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:15.960
- Sarah, Steve, choose either the split

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:17.253
or the steal ball now.

00:49:18.670 --> 00:49:19.503
Hold it up.

00:49:20.610 --> 00:49:24.262
- We're going on the 50 grand
each, I promise you that.

00:49:24.262 --> 00:49:26.929
(intense music)

00:49:31.579 --> 00:49:33.579
- [Host] Split or steal.

00:49:34.476 --> 00:49:35.309
(screaming)

00:49:35.309 --> 00:49:37.476
- So he split, she steals.

00:49:40.749 --> 00:49:41.745
- You never know what's

00:49:41.745 --> 00:49:44.110
coming in this game.
- He has his hands like this.

00:49:44.110 --> 00:49:45.570
- Congratulations, Sarah.

00:49:45.570 --> 00:49:48.140
You have just won
- He's looking kinda mortified

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:49.063
- 100,150 pounds.

00:49:50.408 --> 00:49:52.533
(cheering)

00:49:52.533 --> 00:49:55.613
Steven, Steven, I'm so sorry.

00:49:57.526 --> 00:49:58.443
- Okay, so.

00:50:00.696 --> 00:50:05.420
This is now the second in
my all star game series,

00:50:05.420 --> 00:50:08.020
show series of papers.

00:50:08.020 --> 00:50:10.804
And it's done with one of my Dutch friends

00:50:10.804 --> 00:50:12.968
from the previous paper.

00:50:12.968 --> 00:50:17.850
And so the first question
is, there have been

00:50:18.730 --> 00:50:20.470
literally thousands of papers

00:50:20.470 --> 00:50:22.320
written about the prisoner's dilemma.

00:50:23.600 --> 00:50:26.100
None with stakes this big.

00:50:26.100 --> 00:50:28.730
What happens if you raise the stakes

00:50:28.730 --> 00:50:32.733
to an average of $20,000,

00:50:33.710 --> 00:50:37.649
you get amazingly close to the behavior

00:50:37.649 --> 00:50:41.050
in laboratory experiments
for a few dollars.

00:50:41.050 --> 00:50:44.253
About 45% of the participants split.

00:50:46.720 --> 00:50:47.710
Which means

00:50:50.060 --> 00:50:53.350
half of that, about 20 some percent

00:50:53.350 --> 00:50:54.913
of people leave with money.

00:50:55.981 --> 00:50:59.520
Now we study a bunch of things,

00:50:59.520 --> 00:51:02.320
I'm not gonna go into detail because we're

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:04.490
kind of running out of time.

00:51:04.490 --> 00:51:09.490
Young men steal more
often which means they are

00:51:10.300 --> 00:51:12.877
either rational or jerks.

00:51:12.877 --> 00:51:15.493
We can't distinguish between those.

00:51:17.819 --> 00:51:22.083
There's a question of what
happens with the stake size.

00:51:28.291 --> 00:51:29.850
The answer is

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:34.300
cooperation rates are quite a bit higher

00:51:34.300 --> 00:51:35.873
when the stakes are very low.

00:51:37.945 --> 00:51:42.945
And here's my take on this
and it's the same take

00:51:43.440 --> 00:51:45.610
I gave you on the Deal or No Deal,

00:51:45.610 --> 00:51:50.610
that these stakes look low
in the context of this game.

00:51:52.830 --> 00:51:55.618
And so they know that
they could be playing

00:51:55.618 --> 00:51:59.031
for tens of thousands of pounds.

00:51:59.031 --> 00:52:03.610
If they are only paying for
200, they know it's peanuts,

00:52:03.610 --> 00:52:04.763
why not cooperate?

00:52:07.645 --> 00:52:10.320
But once you get up to serious money,

00:52:10.320 --> 00:52:12.753
stakes isn't doing much.

00:52:12.753 --> 00:52:17.753
And we get about the 40, 45%.

00:52:25.870 --> 00:52:27.913
Yeah, so that's what I just said.

00:52:30.839 --> 00:52:33.130
Another question you could ask,

00:52:33.130 --> 00:52:35.331
so this game is on television.

00:52:35.331 --> 00:52:37.560
Does that matter?

00:52:37.560 --> 00:52:39.150
And of course the answer must be yes,

00:52:39.150 --> 00:52:43.370
but we're not quite sure how it matters.

00:52:43.370 --> 00:52:46.537
In the Deal or No Deal, we
actually ran an experiment

00:52:46.537 --> 00:52:50.090
with students at smaller stakes,

00:52:50.090 --> 00:52:52.250
where we had some play the game in front

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:56.153
of a big audience and some
privately on a computer.

00:52:58.045 --> 00:53:03.045
It turns out, quite
surprisingly at least to me,

00:53:03.467 --> 00:53:08.020
the people in front of the
audience did not take more risk.

00:53:08.020 --> 00:53:09.620
They took a little less.

00:53:09.620 --> 00:53:11.480
I would have predicted
the other way around,

00:53:11.480 --> 00:53:13.173
but the difference wasn't huge.

00:53:15.788 --> 00:53:18.800
So one thing we did here
was we looked at whether

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:23.430
people sort of had some reputational stake

00:53:24.870 --> 00:53:27.460
in appearing to be on this.

00:53:27.460 --> 00:53:31.465
And we did this by just
categorizing their occupations.

00:53:31.465 --> 00:53:36.465
And here's the result that
reputation only mattered

00:53:36.910 --> 00:53:38.841
if the stakes were high.

00:53:38.841 --> 00:53:41.870
And otherwise, it didn't.

00:53:41.870 --> 00:53:44.791
The next thing is, we were interested in,

00:53:44.791 --> 00:53:48.270
there's a bunch of
previous rounds that were

00:53:48.270 --> 00:53:51.001
four players originally and it seems like

00:53:51.001 --> 00:53:55.434
in all game shows you
vote to kick people off.

00:53:55.434 --> 00:53:59.710
There's also a lot of, what game theorists

00:53:59.710 --> 00:54:02.200
would call tube talk in this game,

00:54:02.200 --> 00:54:05.720
where people announce they
have some of these balls

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:08.080
with amounts of money that are hidden

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:10.120
and they announce what they are.

00:54:10.120 --> 00:54:14.394
And what we were interested
in is, if you lie about that,

00:54:14.394 --> 00:54:18.440
does that make you less trustworthy later?

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:20.007
The answer is no.

00:54:20.007 --> 00:54:22.823
It seems that everybody,

00:54:23.820 --> 00:54:26.820
it's common knowledge that everybody lies

00:54:26.820 --> 00:54:29.200
and everybody thinks that everybody lies.

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:31.170
What often happens is

00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:36.070
if a guy is dealt essentially a good hand

00:54:36.070 --> 00:54:39.704
and he has the equivalent
of an ace and a king

00:54:39.704 --> 00:54:44.490
in his hidden balls, he will
truthfully say what he has

00:54:44.490 --> 00:54:47.460
and say, see I'm always
gonna tell you the truth.

00:54:47.460 --> 00:54:51.310
And then in the next round
will lie if it's convenient.

00:54:51.310 --> 00:54:53.550
So they all lie and they
all know they would lie

00:54:53.550 --> 00:54:55.410
so this doesn't matter.

00:54:55.410 --> 00:54:59.230
Now the last thing is,

00:54:59.230 --> 00:55:01.990
one way of characterizing
behavior in this game

00:55:01.990 --> 00:55:04.090
would be four types.

00:55:04.090 --> 00:55:08.403
The first would be, I'll call gameboys.

00:55:09.400 --> 00:55:10.610
They always defect.

00:55:10.610 --> 00:55:12.374
They learned that in
their game theory class

00:55:12.374 --> 00:55:14.791
and so they always defect.

00:55:14.791 --> 00:55:18.830
Then there could be nice guys
and they always cooperate.

00:55:18.830 --> 00:55:22.678
So they always split,
the other ones steal.

00:55:22.678 --> 00:55:27.678
Third guys, I'll call them
conditional tit for tatters.

00:55:29.356 --> 00:55:33.720
They will cooperate with someone who they

00:55:33.720 --> 00:55:37.323
expect to cooperate, and
otherwise they won't.

00:55:39.194 --> 00:55:42.350
Then we have the deep tit for tatters.

00:55:42.350 --> 00:55:46.640
These are ones who
realize, the game theorists

00:55:46.640 --> 00:55:47.970
will know what I'm talking about,

00:55:47.970 --> 00:55:50.313
this is a weak prisoner's dilemma game.

00:55:51.906 --> 00:55:56.306
And they come up with the
following deep realization.

00:55:56.306 --> 00:55:59.763
If the other person is gonna
cooperate, it doesn't matter.

00:56:01.160 --> 00:56:04.702
So they might as well cooperate.

00:56:04.702 --> 00:56:08.850
So they'll cooperate and if
the other guy cooperates,

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:10.230
great, they'll get half.

00:56:10.230 --> 00:56:11.925
If the other guys steals, they were not

00:56:11.925 --> 00:56:14.270
gonna get anything anyway,

00:56:14.270 --> 00:56:17.031
and they might as well look good on TV.

00:56:17.031 --> 00:56:22.031
Now notice A, B, and D are all invariant

00:56:23.123 --> 00:56:25.551
to everything else.

00:56:25.551 --> 00:56:29.220
So what we do is we investigate whether

00:56:29.220 --> 00:56:31.493
we can find any evidence for C.

00:56:32.470 --> 00:56:35.630
So is there any evidence that people take

00:56:35.630 --> 00:56:40.450
into consideration what they
think the other player might do

00:56:40.450 --> 00:56:43.145
and the evidence essentially is no.

00:56:43.145 --> 00:56:47.640
It turns out the only
significant predictor of whether

00:56:47.640 --> 00:56:50.672
someone will cooperate
is whether they explicity

00:56:50.672 --> 00:56:53.197
promise to cooperate.

00:56:53.197 --> 00:56:57.723
In the clip I played you,
he does and she doesn't.

00:56:58.791 --> 00:57:02.470
He says, "I promise you I will cooperate."

00:57:02.470 --> 00:57:04.277
And then she says something like,

00:57:04.277 --> 00:57:07.617
"If I didn't, everyone
would think I'm a jerk

00:57:07.617 --> 00:57:09.207
"and no one would speak to me."

00:57:10.280 --> 00:57:14.043
So if you had our data, you would predict

00:57:14.043 --> 00:57:16.520
that he would cooperate
and she would steal,

00:57:16.520 --> 00:57:19.102
which that turns out to be right.

00:57:19.102 --> 00:57:22.640
There's no version of any
model we could estimate

00:57:22.640 --> 00:57:24.620
in which they seemed to pay attention

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:26.470
to any of those things.

00:57:26.470 --> 00:57:28.926
So I can't tell you what of
the other things they're doing,

00:57:28.926 --> 00:57:32.120
but they don't seem to be doing

00:57:32.120 --> 00:57:34.263
this conditional cooperation.

00:57:37.107 --> 00:57:40.990
Point one is good economics requires

00:57:41.891 --> 00:57:45.810
sensible models of how real people behave.

00:57:45.810 --> 00:57:50.810
That's really the radical
departure I had 30 years ago.

00:57:51.600 --> 00:57:55.590
You might worry or
wonder, what does this say

00:57:55.590 --> 00:57:58.160
about public policy, but
you have to come back

00:57:58.160 --> 00:57:59.773
tomorrow to find out.

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:03.021
Thank you very much.

00:58:03.021 --> 00:58:05.438
(applauding)

00:58:09.375 --> 00:58:11.792
(soft music)

